  <h2>Pump on a Sensible Schedule</h2>
  <p>
    This is the foundation. Solids accumulate no matter what, and pumping removes them before they can
    carry over into the drain field. There's no universal interval — it depends on tank size,
    household size, and water habits — so the best guide is how full the tank actually was at the last
    service. Ask the provider, and adjust from there. Our guide on
    <a href="/how-often-to-pump-septic-tank/">how often to pump</a> walks through the factors.
  </p>

  <h2>Manage Water Use</h2>
  <p>
    A septic system handles a steady flow far better than sudden surges. A few habits make a real
    difference:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Fix running toilets and dripping fixtures promptly — a running toilet can quietly flood a drain field with clean water all day.</li>
    <li>Spread laundry across the week rather than doing many loads in one day.</li>
    <li>Direct roof, gutter, and surface drainage away from the tank and drain field.</li>
    <li>Be mindful of load spikes — houseguests, parties, and holiday weekends all add up.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Protect the Drains</h2>
  <p>
    The system is designed for wastewater and what naturally breaks down — nothing else. Keeping the
    following out prevents clogs and protects the biology the tank relies on:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>No wipes — including the ones labeled "flushable," which don't break down like toilet paper.</li>
    <li>No grease, fats, or cooking oils down the kitchen sink.</li>
    <li>No paint, solvents, or harsh chemical dumps that disrupt the tank's bacteria.</li>
    <li>Minimal garbage-disposal use — compost or bin food waste instead, since disposals accelerate solids buildup.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Protect the Drain Field</h2>
  <p>
    The field is the expensive part, and it needs air and space to work:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Keep vehicles, heavy equipment, and structures off the drain field — compaction damages it.</li>
    <li>Keep deep-rooted trees and shrubs well away from the field lines.</li>
    <li>Maintain grass cover, which helps the field breathe and shed rainwater.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Watch for Warning Signs</h2>
  <p>
    Catching a problem early is the difference between a routine fix and a major repair. Act on slow
    drains throughout the house, gurgling after water use, odors indoors or outside, wet or unusually
    green areas over the field, any system alarm, and backups — even ones that seem to clear on their
    own. Our guides on <a href="/resources/septic-problems/">warning signs</a> and
    <a href="/signs-a-septic-tank-may-be-full/">a tank that may be full</a> cover what each can mean.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep Records</h2>
  <p>
    A little paperwork pays off for years. Note:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>The tank's location, measured from two fixed points on the house.</li>
    <li>Lid depth and what it takes to open them.</li>
    <li>Every service date and what was done.</li>
    <li>The provider's observations each visit — sludge levels, baffle condition, anything to watch.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    These records make future service faster and cheaper and add credibility when selling. To put the
    checklist into motion, <a href="/request-service/">request septic service</a> and start the record
    with what the provider finds.
  </p>
